Question 1

(SMSS 14.3, 14.4, merged & modified)

(Data file: house.selling.price.2 from smss R package)

For the house.selling.price.2 data the tables below show a correlation matrix and a model fit using four predictors of selling price. With these four predictors,

1A For backward elimination, which variable would be deleted first? Why?

For backward elimination, Beds would be removed first since it has the largest p-value compared to the other predictors (0.487)

1B For forward selection, which variable would be added first? Why?

For forward elimination, we would add Size to the model first. Since Size and New have similar p-values, the correlation matrix reinforces the selection of Size first since it has a higher correlation to price compared to New.

1C Why do you think that BEDS has such a large P-value in the multiple regression model, even though it has a substantial correlation with PRICE?

I think that Beds has such a large p-value in the regression model because it is somewhat redundant information. Size its capturing the overall size of the house, including bedrooms,meaning Beds isn’t really adding anything new to the model. Beds could be highly correlated with price since more beds means larger size, but we already have Size accounting for a large portion of the variation.

1D Using software with these four predictors, find the model that would be selected using each criterion: R2, Adjusted R2, PRESS, AIC, BIC

1E Explain which model you prefer and why.

I prefer the SNB model, which includes Size, New and Bath, because it seems to be the best model for almost all comparisons. It has the lowest PRESS, AIC, and BIC compared to the other models and has a larger R2 adjusted as well. The model containing all variables does have a higher R2, but only by a small margin. Bedrooms do not seem to add any additional information to the model which is why I choose the model with all except Bedrooms.

Question 2

(Data file: trees from base R) From the documentation: “This data set provides measurements of the diameter, height and volume of timber in 31 felled black cherry trees. Note that the diameter (in inches) is erroneously labelled Girth in the data. It is measured at 4 ft 6 in above the ground.”

Tree volume estimation is a big deal, especially in the lumber industry. Use the trees data to build a basic model of tree volume prediction. In particular,

2A Fit a multiple regression model withthe Volume as the outcome and Girth and Height as the explanatory variables

2B Run regression diagnostic plots on the model. Based on the plots, do you think any of the regression assumptions is violated?

The plots suggest that there are regression assumptions being violated, specifically linearity and constant variance. The residuals do not form a straight line, violating linearity, and the residuals do not form a horizontal band, violating constant variance.

Question 3

(inspired by ALR 9.16)

(Data file: florida in alr R package)

In the 2000 election for U.S. president, the counting of votes in Florida was controversial. In Palm Beach County in south Florida, for example, voters used a so-called butterfly ballot. Some believe that the layout of the ballot caused some voters to cast votes for Buchanan when their intended choice was Gore.

The data has variables for the number of votes for each candidate—Gore, Bush, and Buchanan. Run a simple linear regression model where the Buchanan vote is the outcome and the Bush vote is the explanatory variable. Produce the regression diagnostic plots. Is Palm Beach County an outlier based on the diagnostic plots? Why or why not?

PART 2 (Final Project)

1 What is your research question for the final project?

I was able to find to a dataset from Kaggle that contained results from an online personality test. For the purposes of this project, the research question is: Why do most people score very high on questions relating to AGR or OPN?

2 What is your hypothesis (i.e. an answer to the research question) that you want to test?

I’d like to test whether or not the time spent answering each section is the reason for this unequal categorization. If more people have AGR or OPN as their dominant trait, then they are most likely spending more time on answering questions specific to those categories.

3B Plot the relationships between key variables. You can do this any way you want, but one straightforward way of doing this would be with the pairs() function or other scatter plots / box plots. Interpret what you see.

The first plot shows us that more people are classified as AGR or OPN as their dominant trait compared to the other 3 traits. This helps explain why on the second graph, the majority of observations are either purple or orange. Additionally, the second graph shows how much time it took for respondents to take the test, with a majority of participants completing the test in 5 minutes or less.
